logan abassi — minustah / getty images in the aftermath of the quake , efforts by citizens and international aid organizations to provide medical assistance , food , and water to survivors were hampered by the failure of the electric power system ( which already was unreliable ) , loss of communication lines , and roads blocked with debris .
a week after the event , little aid had reached beyond port-au-prince ; after another week , supplies were being distributed only sporadically to other urban areas .
operations to rescue those trapped under the wreckage — which had freed over 100 people — had mostly ceased two weeks into the crisis , as hope that anyone could have survived for that length of time without food or water began to fade .
however , there were still occasional recoveries of people who had managed to survive such confinement for weeks by rationing the meagre supplies available to them .
